`crates/ctx-cage/src/lifecycle/` implements the three-phase execution of one caged `claude` session ‚Äî prepare, run, teardown ‚Äî and is the thing `ctx-cage`'s entry point calls after argv parsing. Depending on this directory gets you `execute(Resolved) -> RunOutcome`: a guaranteed prepare‚Üírun‚Üíteardown sequence with best-effort cleanup, an exit code, and optional proxy diagnostics.

The phases share `Prep`, minted by `prepare.rs` and consumed by `env.rs`, `run.rs`/`run/`, and finally destroyed by `teardown.rs` ‚Äî nothing else may read or write outside `prep.rundir`. Billed modes (Task/Interactive) pull in extra machinery not touched by SelfTestStub: `ensure_clean_tree` (prepare.rs), `ClaudeRuntime` resolution, the API proxy thread + socat relay + preflight/claude_invocation handoff (run.rs and run/), and the clearenv assembly in `env.rs` that omits `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` in favor of a bound OAuth credential. Target root must be canonicalized before reaching `env.rs`'s bwrap config, per ADR-046. Proxy/diagnostic failures never override the cage's exit code (ADR-027) ‚Äî this rule spans `run.rs`, `run/`, and the outcome type in `mod.rs`.

`cagevars.rs` is orthogonal to the phase pipeline: it's a startup-time env preload (before `Resolved` even exists), sharing only the allowlist convention with `ctx-summarize`'s dotenv parser and deliberately excluding the ADR-013 spend-consent variable. `mod.rs` is the orchestrator and `Resolved`/`RunOutcome` owner; `prepare.rs` mints the rundir and validates preconditions; `env.rs` resolves binds/env for bwrap; `run.rs` + `run/` execute and monitor the child; `teardown.rs` cleans up unconditionally.

No intent.md exists for this directory, so no divergence check is possible.